Cool, we'll DM on specific examples if that's helpful. The main gist is just that I think it's a missed opportunity to not have a simpler (and optionally anonymous) way to send feedback.

In terms of figuring out the right channel for the right feedback, y'all have said that `/feedback` submissions are more likely to be prioritized if there is similar feedback coming from more than one person. So I've wanted to default to posting there over sending a DM (especially if it's not urgent) to help the team's prioritization process and avoid blowing up your DMs.
@undefined and I ran together from start to finish

First off, thanks for your feedback on ns.com/feedback @undefined. 

I'll DM you to understand what feedback you wanted to share so we can understand (1) what the right channel is and (2) potential ways to reduce friction.

Meanwhile, I'll highlight two other avenues: 

- Message any NS Core staff member on Discord or talk to us irl to share feedback 
- Complete ns.com/fixit for maintenance requests

We review responses to ns.com/feedback periodically but as I mentioned above you can always share feedback with NS Core staff if it's time sensitive or critical to relay directly.

@undefined @undefined @undefined It's great that `/feedback` exists. But I wish I could submit feedback without being required to **1.** give an NPS score **2.** input decisions about staying at NS past Dec 23 and **3.** provide an email.

When I provide an NPS score and "past Dec 23rd" decision, I feel like it seems like those data points are the most important part of the submission. However, every time I've filled this form out, I've wanted the focus to be on the feedback itself (not NPS score). I don't think this is your intention, but I think it's also easy to start wondering if the feedback is only considered based on how you score the NPS and how you mark the "past Dec 23rd" question. If y'all are doing a Superhuman-style PMF-metric on the feedback and that's why you're collecting this, I get it. But, as a community member, it just feels like a lot to categorize myself this way when I want to share feedback. **The net result is friction to using `/feedback`**.

Also, I'm sure you're missing out on valuable feedback from folks by requiring an email address to submit the form. I can understand the pros-and-cons of allowing anonymous feedback, but I think there's important signal you're not getting because of this. **Again, the net result is friction to using `/feedback`**.

As a last note — it would be great to know if y'all actually have the bandwidth to regularly review `/feedback` at the moment. It would be fine if the honest answer was "no", but would be good to know and set expectations.

some things about training load:

today in the gym our trainer mentioned casually that we are almost done training base aerobic fitness.

we are actually in a 3 months program with them and it reminded me of one of the books i got recommended from a biker friend (cyclists training bible).

not sure where we are exactly but i suppose we are somewhere in "train to train" phase still. the goal is to actually do resistance training on the weights. 

for the marathon you are also still in "train to train". in biking this is lots of looooong rides very slow (zone 2), also time in the gym for core strength and stretching (helps with recovery and injury prevention).

i did about 2 months "prepare to train" (jan/feb), 3 months of "train to train" (mar-may) and 3 weeks of "train to race" , and 1 week of "taper for race" for my event. the week after the event i rode the most km and elevation in my life, which means I was at peak for the race and race ready for 1 week. then i got a bit tired and reduced load "rest and recover" and just enjoying my fitness in the swiss and french alps.

so you can just focus right now on building the routine, getting your nutrition and hydration sorted. start running in the morning e.g. after early workout to see what the temperatures feel like - maybe it's easier than in the evening, also less chance of rain or wet pavement.

I thought about the meeting a bit and here is the tl:dr;

- Khang: understands that good food is super relevant, you especially need carbs which is in rice, wheat, quinoa etc. so you need to have this "fuel".
- Em: understands hydration: drink a large dose of electrolytes before running. this helps your body absorb water better and stay hydrated. since duration is around 1 to 1.5h it's not such a big issue. if you do not consume electrolytes you dilute the salts in your body and you may crash, hit wall and all the other terms happening. this is not because you did not train enough, it's because your hydration strategy was non existent.
 - Cramps: you need magnesium to prevent cramps. and potassium is also good.
- Profile: take it easy: understand if your run is flat or has elevation. It's better to finish strong then to start to fast, get cramp, tear muscle etc. (I had all of this on my road bike race 5km in. never had an issue with this in non race environment. thankfully had enough experience to go through the pain and could finish). 
- In the week before you have taper week and load will go down to leverage hyper compensation of the body to be in peak "form".
- Always always always put your health first. 
- Stretch a lot, best daily for 30 minutes.

I was so dialed in on my race that the week after 2 days of rest I was still riding the most I have done in my life even while training for the big event. It was effortless. That was the real achievement.

So take it easy. Listen to your body.

The modern interpretation of Misogi, which Easter applies in the context of personal growth, is more metaphorical—it’s about taking on a challenge that seems nearly impossible, where the odds of failure are high but the goal is to test your limits and grow through discomfort.

**Key Elements of Modern Misogi:**

**1.** Uncomfortable Challenge: It should be something so difficult that there’s a good chance you might not finish it. It’s about finding the edges of your physical and mental endurance.
